### Distributive Conditional Types

When a conditional type is applied to a union, TypeScript automatically distributes it across each union member. This means `T extends U ? X : Y` applied to `A | B` results in `(A extends U ? X : Y) | (B extends U ? X : Y)`, not the conditional applied to the entire union.

Distribution is automatic for conditional types in type parameters. Wrap the conditional in an array to prevent distribution if you need to treat the union as a single entity.

```typescript
type IsString<T> = T extends string ? true : false;

type Result1 = IsString<string | number>; // true | false (distributed)

type IsStringArray<T> = T extends string ? true : false;
type NoDistribute<T> = [T] extends [string] ? true : false;
type Result2 = NoDistribute<string | number>; // false (not distributed)

type Exclude<T, U> = T extends U ? never : T;
type Without = Exclude<'a' | 'b' | 'c', 'b'>; // 'a' | 'c'

type Filter<T, U> = T extends U ? T : never;
type OnlyStrings = Filter<string | number | boolean, string>; // string
```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates don't realize distribution happens by default—they expect `never` but get `true | false` from distributive conditionals applied to unions.

### Type-Safe Event Emitter

A type-safe event emitter uses mapped types and conditional types to ensure listeners match event signatures. Define an event map as a type, then use it to validate both `emit()` and `on()` operations at compile-time.

The key is mapping event names to payloads, then using function overloads or conditional logic to extract the correct payload type for each event. This prevents listeners from receiving unexpected data.

```typescript
type EventMap = {
  user_login: { userId: number };
  user_logout: { timestamp: number };
  message: { text: string; author: string };
};

class EventEmitter<Events extends Record<string, any>> {
  private listeners: Map<string, Set<Function>> = new Map();

  on<K extends keyof Events>(
    event: K,
    listener: (payload: Events[K]) => void
  ): void {
    if (!this.listeners.has(event as string)) {
      this.listeners.set(event as string, new Set());
    }
    this.listeners.get(event as string)!.add(listener);
  }

  emit<K extends keyof Events>(event: K, payload: Events[K]): void {
    this.listeners.get(event as string)?.forEach(l => l(payload));
  }
}

const emitter = new EventEmitter<EventMap>();
emitter.on('user_login', (p) => console.log(p.userId)); // ✓
// emitter.on('user_login', (p) => p.text); // ✗ Property 'text' doesn't exist
```


**Common interview trap:** Candidates forget to use generics in the method signatures—without `<K extends keyof Events>`, the payload type becomes `any` and type safety is lost.

