### Type-Safe Builder with Required Field Tracking

Track which fields have been set using a generic union parameter. The trick is that `build()` is only present in the type when the tracked set equals the full set of required keys, enforced via `[keyof T] extends [Done]` (non-distributive check).

```typescript
interface User { name: string; email: string; age: number }

class UserBuilder<Done extends keyof User = never> {
  private data: Partial<User> = {};

  setName(name: string): UserBuilder<Done | 'name'> {
    this.data.name = name;
    return this as any;
  }

  setEmail(email: string): UserBuilder<Done | 'email'> {
    this.data.email = email;
    return this as any;
  }

  setAge(age: number): UserBuilder<Done | 'age'> {
    this.data.age = age;
    return this as any;
  }

  // build() only exists when Done includes ALL keys of User
  build(this: UserBuilder<keyof User>): User {
    return this.data as User;
  }
}

// ✓ All required fields set — build() is available
const user = new UserBuilder()
  .setName('Alice')
  .setEmail('alice@example.com')
  .setAge(30)
  .build();

// ✗ Missing .setAge() — TypeScript error on .build():
// "The 'this' context of type UserBuilder<'name' | 'email'> is not assignable
//  to method's 'this' of type UserBuilder<keyof User>"
const incomplete = new UserBuilder().setName('Bob').setEmail('b@b.com').build();
```

The `build(this: UserBuilder<keyof User>)` signature uses a typed `this` parameter to enforce that `Done` must equal `keyof User` before the call is allowed.

**Common interview trap:** Using `Set extends keyof T` as the condition for `build()` — this is always `true` since `Set` is constrained to `keyof T`. The correct check is the reverse: `[keyof T] extends [Set]` (wrapped in `[]` to prevent distributivity), which is only true when all keys of `T` are in `Set`.

